    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if OpenAI's GPT-5.3 model is made available to the general public by the specified date (ET). Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No.\"\n\nGPT-5.3 refers to a product explicitly named GPT-5.3, or a general-purpose variant that is recognized as a direct successor to GPT-5.2, similar to the core-version progression from GPT-5.1 to GPT-5.2. \n\nModel releases that do not resemble this core version progression, such as task-specialized models (e.g., GPT-Codex/Transcribe), cost-efficiency variants (e.g., Nano/Mini), reasoning models of the o-series family, as well as products labeled GPT-6 or similar, will not qualify for this market.\n\nFor this market to resolve to \"Yes,\" a qualifying model must be launched and publicly accessible, including via open beta or open rolling waitlist signups. A closed beta or any form of private access will not suffice. The release must be clearly defined and publicly announced by OpenAI as being accessible to the general public.\n\nThe primary resolution source for this market will be official information from OpenAI, with additional verification from a consensus of credible reporting.",
    "outcome": "March 31",
    "explanation": "\n## Executive Summary\nThe prediction market for the release date of GPT-5.3 ultimately resolved to the \"March 31\" bucket because OpenAI employed a staggered release strategy that pushed the main model launch past the earlier February deadlines. Initial speculation and the launch of the specialized GPT-5.3-Codex on February 18 caused temporary market belief that the \"February 20\" or \"February 28\" options would win. However, because Codex was deemed a specialized tool rather than the full general release, it did not satisfy the resolution criteria. The subsequent release of GPT-5.3 Instant on March 3 officially fulfilled the criteria, missing the February 28 deadline and landing firmly in the March 31 resolution window.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- **2026-02-18:** OpenAI launched the specialized coding model GPT-5.3-Codex, prompting initial market shifts favoring early resolution ([art_tech_20260218_003_9e84c56d], [art_tech_20260218_007_70dad21a]).\n- **2026-02-20:** Market sentiment peaked as predictors debated whether the Codex release would trigger an early resolution for the \"February 20\" bucket ([art_tech_20260220_009_e436151d]).\n- **2026-02-23 to 2026-02-25:** Rumors of the main GPT-5.3 model being in A/B testing and early Microsoft integrations kept hopes alive for a \"February 28\" release ([art_tech_20260223_002_5d4af747], [art_tech_20260225_008_9704365b]).\n- **2026-03-03:** OpenAI officially released GPT-5.3 Instant to the general public, fulfilling the core release criteria just after the February deadline had passed ([art_tech_20260303_010_e217208e], [art_tech_20260303_015_3803f036]).\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nOpenAI's product strategy involved a phased rollout of the GPT-5.3 family, starting with specialized applications. This strategy caused the initial release of GPT-5.3-Codex on February 18 ([art_tech_20260218_003_9e84c56d]), which triggered premature market optimism that the release criteria had been met before February 20. However, the specialized nature of Codex meant it was not counted as the primary GPT-5.3 release, which led to a market correction. The subsequent delay of the broader model meant it missed the February 28 bucket. Ultimately, the general release of GPT-5.3 Instant on March 3 ([art_tech_20260303_010_e217208e]) resulted in the resolution falling into the March 31 category, because it was the first available bucket after the March 3 launch.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nThe strongest countervailing factor was the release of GPT-5.3-Codex on February 18. Many market participants reasonably believed that any official model bearing the \"GPT-5.3\" moniker would satisfy the resolution criteria, pushing the \"February 20\" and \"February 28\" options higher. This force was overwhelmed by the specific resolution rules (or consensus interpretation) which evidently required a general ChatGPT/API release rather than a specialized coding assistant extension.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n- **E1: Release of GPT-5.3-Codex**\n  - Title: OpenAI releases GPT-5.3-Codex\n  - Date: 2026-02-18\n  - Why it matters causally: Spiked early market predictions but failed to meet the criteria for a general release.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_tech_20260218_003_9e84c56d], [art_tech_20260218_007_70dad21a]\n\n- **E2: Release of GPT-5.3 Instant**\n  - Title: OpenAI releases GPT-5.3 Instant\n  - Date: 2026-03-03\n  - Why it matters causally: The actual event that fulfilled the question's criteria, dictating the final \"March 31\" outcome since it missed February 28.\n  - Source article IDs: [art_tech_20260303_010_e217208e], [art_tech_20260303_015_3803f036]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| GPT-5.3-Codex released | [art_tech_20260218_003_9e84c56d], [art_tech_20260218_007_70dad21a] | 2026-02-18 | 1.0 | Clear model drop date |\n| GPT-5.3 Instant released | [art_tech_20260303_010_e217208e], [art_tech_20260303_015_3803f036] | 2026-03-03 | 1.0 | General release that resolved the market |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe main uncertainty was whether the market administrators would count \"GPT-5.3-Codex\" as a valid GPT-5.3 release. If it had been counted, the outcome would have resolved to February 20. The staggered naming convention (Codex vs. Instant) created definitional ambiguity that drove the significant price volatility in mid-to-late February.\n",
